  "slug": "poulet-basquaise",
  "title": "Poulet Basquaise",
  "subtitle": "Basque chicken with peppers and tomatoes",
  "excerpt": "Chicken thighs braised in a warm, peppery sauce of softened peppers, tomatoes, white wine, and smoked paprika. A dish from the French Basque country with Iberian flavours.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Poulet à la basquaise is documented in Julia Child, Louisette Bertholle, and Simone Beck, Mastering the Art of French Cooking (1961) and Frédérick E. Grasser-Hermé, La Cuisine du Pays Basque (2004). The Basque Country (on both the French and Spanish sides) shares this dish, with minor variations in the type of pepper used.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Poulet basquaise is a one-pot braise. Everything goes into the casserole in sequence, the lid goes on, and the chicken cooks in the fragrant steam of peppers, tomatoes, and wine. The key step is browning the chicken properly before the braising begins. The deep gold crust gives the sauce its body and colour."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The dish has a mild heat from the peppers and a quiet smokiness from the paprika. The Basque version uses an Espelette pepper (a dried chilli grown in the Basque Country); smoked paprika is the accessible substitute that achieves a similar result.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
