      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brown the chicken",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Season the chicken thighs. Heat the olive oil in a large casserole over medium-high heat. Brown the thighs skin-side down for 5 to 6 minutes until the skin is deep gold and crisp. Turn and brown the other side for 3 minutes. Transfer to a plate.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build the sauce and braise",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "In the same casserole, cook the onion for 8 minutes until soft. Add the garlic and paprika, stir for 1 minute. Add the peppers and cook for 5 minutes. Add the wine and let it bubble for 2 minutes. Add the tinned tomatoes, thyme, and bay leaves. Return the chicken thighs to the casserole, skin-side up. Cover and cook over medium-low heat for 30 to 35 minutes until the chicken is cooked through. Remove the lid for the last 10 minutes to let the skin crisp slightly. Season and scatter with parsley.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Remove the lid for the final 10 minutes; this allows the skin to dry and crisp",
              "cause": "Steam from the lid condenses and softens the skin",
              "symptom": "Skin is soggy"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Cook uncovered for longer; crush some of the tomatoes against the pan to release their pulp and help the sauce thicken",
              "cause": "Too much liquid from the tinned tomatoes and wine",
              "symptom": "Sauce is too watery"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Poulet basquaise sits at the intersection of French and Spanish cooking, the Basque Country straddles the border and its cuisine reflects both. The pepper-tomato combination (piperade) and the smoked paprika are Iberian in spirit; the wine-braised one-pot method is firmly French. It is summer food: made when peppers are good and cheap, served with crusty bread or rice.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
